definitions.definition: A bundle , twist , braid , or woven strip of cord , fabric , fibre , or other porous material in a candle , oil lamp, kerosene heater, or the like, that draws up liquid fuel , such as melted tallow , wax , or the oil, delivering it to the base of the flame for conversion to gases and burning; any other length of material burned for illumination in small successive portions.
examples: Trim the wick fairly short, so that the flame does not smoke.

definitions.definition: Any piece of porous material that conveys liquid by capillary action , such as a strip of gauze placed in a wound to serve as a drain .
( curling ) A narrow opening in the field, flanked by other players' stones.
( curling ) A shot where the played stone touches a stationary stone just enough that the played stone changes direction.

definitions.definition: ( British , dialect , chiefly East Anglia and Essex ) A farm , especially a dairy farm.

main_definition: ( British , dialect , chiefly East Anglia and Essex ) A farm , especially a dairy farm.

definitions.definition: ( British , obsolete , dialect , chiefly Yorkshire ) Liveliness ; life .
( British , dialect , chiefly Yorkshire ) The growing part of a plant nearest to the roots.
examples: Fed close? Why, it's eaten into t' hard wick . (spoken of a pasture which has been fed very close)

definitions.definition: ( British , dialect , chiefly Yorkshire , horticulture ) (Usually plural) The parts of weed roots that remain viable in the ground after inadequate digging prior to cultivation.
( British , dialect , chiefly Yorkshire ) A maggot .

( obsolete or dialectal ) A grove ; a hollow .
( now dialectal ) A corner of the mouth or eye .
